Second part of the course will focus on practical data management and publishing using PlutoF platform (https://plutof.ut.ee). PlutoF is a data management system which targets biological data and data generated by Citizen Scientists. Please check if this part of the course is useful for you. For example you have already biodiversity data or willing to gather such data during the course. Simple bird observations are welcome too. Then sign in. It is also important to understand that both parts of the course can be attended separately. If you have additional questions please contact teachers.Objectives/eesmärkid:  Part 1: Understanding Open Science, Open Access to publications and research data management throughout the research data lifecycle; how to create and follow the data management plan; How to find and use open research data Part 2: Doctoral students' own research data has been published on the PlutoF platform, it has been allocated a DOI, which allows the citing of the data on the Web of Science Data Citation IndexLearning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Having passed the course the students *	have knowledge about Open Science and Open Access to publications *	are aware of and familiar with the main principles open and FAIR data and the research data life cycle; *	are able to manage, publish and archive their data; *	are able to find research data in data repositories of the world, and understand, reuse and cite the data; *	can create the data management plan; *	can publish and manage their data on the PlutoF platform.
